1.content:
Absolutely—here’s a tight game plan to let Claude Code analyze your homepage and then redesign it with animated product cards, using MCPs that specialize in web auditing and live-page interaction.

What to install (MCPs that actually help with UI/UX work)

Lighthouse MCP – one-command performance/SEO/PWA audits with Core Web Vitals; perfect for “why is this slow / what should I fix first?” 
GitHub
+1
playbooks.com
Glama – MCP Hosting Platform

Axe / A11y MCP – automated accessibility scans (WCAG), actionable findings Claude can fix. Multiple maintained implementations exist. 
Deque
GitHub
LobeHub
PulseMCP

Playwright MCP (Microsoft) – lets Claude interact with your page structure via accessibility trees and take precise DOM-aware actions; great for extracting sections, confirming selectors, and validating changes. 
GitHub

Screenshot MCP (Playwright-based) – fast “before/after” snapshots of your running site or localhost to verify layout and visual diffs. 
LobeHub
Glama – MCP Hosting Platform
PulseMCP

(Optional) Brave Search MCP – quick competitive scans and design inspiration queries without leaving Claude. 
Reddit

You already set up Vercel MCP for deployments; keep that for preview/production push + logs. (It complements the audit/analysis MCPs.)

Install / add commands (Claude Code)

Make sure your Claude Code CLI is up to date first (npm i -g @anthropic-ai/claude-code). Then add servers.

Lighthouse MCP (Node 16+; Chrome/Chromium required):

# Example: priyankark/lighthouse-mcp (any Lighthouse MCP with get_performance_score is fine)
npx -y @priyankark/lighthouse-mcp@latest
# In another terminal, add it to Claude Code (http/SSE endpoint given by the server)
claude mcp add --transport http lighthouse http://localhost:3333


GitHub
playbooks.com
Glama – MCP Hosting Platform

Axe / A11y MCP (choose one):

# PyPI variant (mcp-axe)
pip install mcp-axe
mcp-axe serve --port 4545
claude mcp add --transport http a11y http://localhost:4545


—or—

# Node variant (a11y-mcp)
npx -y a11y-mcp@latest
claude mcp add --transport http a11y http://localhost:4545


LobeHub
GitHub
Medium

Playwright MCP (Microsoft):

# Start the server (see repo README for port/flags)
npx -y playwright-mcp@latest
claude mcp add --transport http playwright http://localhost:3000


GitHub

Screenshot MCP:

npx -y @bradydouthit/screenshot-mcp@latest
claude mcp add --transport http screenshot http://localhost:4050


LobeHub

(Optional) Brave Search MCP:

npx -y @brave/brave-search-mcp-server
claude mcp add --transport stdio brave npx -- -y @brave/brave-search-mcp-server


Reddit

Use /mcp inside Claude Code to confirm each server is connected and to complete any auth flows.

How to use them together (fast workflow)

Screenshot your current homepage (prod or localhost) → keep as “baseline.” 
LobeHub

Lighthouse run → get performance, SEO, PWA, and best-practices scores + prioritized fixes. 
GitHub

Axe run → get a11y violations (+ quick-fix suggestions). 
Deque
GitHub

Playwright → let Claude read the accessibility tree / DOM to precisely locate the “red-boxed” sections you marked for removal/redesign and confirm selectors safely. 
GitHub

Iterate changes → Screenshot again for diff; rerun Lighthouse + Axe to verify improvements. 
GitHub

Do you need a separate “agent”?

Not really. Claude Code already orchestrates MCP tools inline. You can simulate an agentic loop by asking Claude to:

run Lighthouse/Axe → summarize issues → propose code → apply diffs → re-run audits.
If you later want a more autonomous loop, add a thin script or use a workflow runner, but you don’t need it to get excellent results today. 
Anthropic

Drop-in “Final Prompt” for the redesign

Paste this as your message in Claude Code (after the MCPs are connected). Replace the URL and file paths where noted.

Role: You are a senior Frontend/UX engineer and design systems lead. You will analyze my homepage and produce a production-ready redesign and code diffs.
Context/Goals:

Site URL (prod or http://localhost:3000): <YOUR_URL_HERE>

There are several sections outlined with red squares in my current design. Delete or completely redesign those sections now.

I need at least 4 product cards that are visually stunning with React + Framer Motion micro-interactions (hover, reveal, subtle parallax/tilt, entrance animations), TailwindCSS, and semantic HTML. Cards must be responsive, keyboard-navigable, and meet WCAG 2.1 AA.

Keep the overall brand vibe (“Moonlight Analytica” minimal, modern).

Generate mobile-first markup and styles.

Targets: Lighthouse ≥ 95 Perf / 100 SEO / 100 Best Practices on mobile test; fix all Axe critical/serious issues; ship with basic SEO (title/meta/OG), schema.org Product markup, and image alt.

Tools available (MCP): Lighthouse, Axe, Playwright, Screenshot, Vercel.

Plan (execute step-by-step and show me results between steps):

Screenshot current homepage, save as /tmp/homepage-before.png.

Run Lighthouse (mobile emulation) on the homepage. Summarize top issues + quick wins (render-blocking, font loading, image formats, CLS culprits).

Run Axe on the homepage. Summarize violations with selectors, why it matters, and fix snippets.

Use Playwright to:

Extract the DOM structure and locate elements corresponding to my red-boxed areas; confirm the selectors you will remove/replace.

Identify where to insert the new 4-card product grid.

Propose a new IA/wireframe (sections order, headings). Then produce the React code:

A self-contained Products.tsx with Framer Motion animations (staggered entrance, hover tilt/reveal), Tailwind classes, and ARIA labels.

A refactor of the page (e.g., app/page.tsx or src/pages/index.tsx) removing/redesigning all red-boxed areas.

Ensure cards have: title, short description, CTA, small tag list, optional badge; prefers reduced motion when prefers-reduced-motion is set.

Generate diffs/patches only (no unrelated files). Include any Tailwind config additions if needed.

Re-run Axe and Lighthouse. Report new scores and remaining gaps.

Screenshot again as /tmp/homepage-after.png. Show a before/after summary (pixels, CLS fixes, bundle size impact).

Prepare a commit message and Vercel deploy instructions.

Acceptance criteria:

Red-boxed sections are deleted or redesigned.

4 animated product cards look premium, feel fast, and are fully accessible.

Mobile Lighthouse ≥ 95 Perf; all critical/serious Axe issues resolved.

Clear diffs and instructions to deploy on Vercel.

Now run Step 1 and show me the /tmp/homepage-before.png screenshot. Then proceed step-by-step.

Handy commands to kick off inside Claude Code

After pasting the prompt above:

“Use Screenshot MCP to capture the homepage now.” 
LobeHub

“Run Lighthouse on the homepage (mobile). Paste key metrics + recommendations.” 
GitHub

“Run Axe and list violations grouped by severity with selectors.” 
GitHub

“Use Playwright MCP to confirm selectors for the red-boxed areas and proposed insertion point for the product grid.” 
GitHub

1.content:
Got you. The issue you’re hitting is that the Brave MCP server defaults to **HTTP** (port 8080), but **Claude Code expects STDIO**. Your config doesn’t pass the transport flag, so Claude can’t attach and times out.

Here’s the quick fix + a couple of sanity checks:

## 1) Use the right command **and** force STDIO

Update your MCP config to add the `--transport stdio` args (and keep your API key in env).

**VS Code (`.vscode/mcp.json`) or Claude Code user settings JSON:**

```json
{
  "servers": {
    "brave-search": {
      "command": "npx",
      "args": ["-y", "@brave/brave-search-mcp-server", "--transport", "stdio"],
      "env": {
        "BRAVE_API_KEY": "BSA5cK5ZYURpBc1Gm-oQcHKht3MJple"
      }
    }
  }
}
```

Brave’s own README shows `--transport stdio` and the `BRAVE_API_KEY` env var; default transport is **http**, so that flag is required for Claude Code. ([GitHub][1])

> If you prefer Claude Desktop instead of VS Code, Brave’s guide shows a parallel JSON config—just the same args with `--transport stdio`. ([Brave][2])

## 2) Re-test from a terminal

```bash
# One-off sanity check (should NOT say 0.0.0.0:8080; it should just stream stdio)
BRAVE_API_KEY="BSA..." npx -y @brave/brave-search-mcp-server --transport stdio
```

If you see it trying to bind to port 8080 again, the flag didn’t take. The repo documents both env and CLI options (including `--transport`). ([GitHub][1])

## 3) (Windows) make sure `npx` is resolvable for Claude Code

Sometimes Claude’s spawned process doesn’t inherit your shell PATH. If `claude mcp list` still fails, point to `npx` explicitly, e.g.:

```json
"command": "C:\\Users\\<you>\\AppData\\Roaming\\nvm\\v22.4.1\\npx.cmd"
```

There are a bunch of PATH-related threads that boil down to this exact fix. ([Stack Overflow][3])

## 4) Bump startup timeout if needed

If you still get “Command timed out after 5s”, increase the MCP startup timeout. Claude Code honors an env var like:

```bash
# e.g. 15s
set MCP_TIMEOUT=15000   # (PowerShell: $env:MCP_TIMEOUT = "15000")
```

Then restart Claude Code and re-run `claude mcp list`. (Docs mention configuring MCP server startup timeout via `MCP_TIMEOUT`.) ([Anthropic][4])

## 5) Fix your filesystem server line (optional but you’ll want it)

Your error also shows:

```
filesystem: npx -y @modelcontextprotocol/server-filesystem C:/Users/alima - ✗ Failed to connect
```

On Windows, pass the path as a separate arg and use proper quoting/backslashes. Example:

```json
"filesystem": {
  "command": "npx",
  "args": ["-y", "@modelcontextprotocol/server-filesystem", "C:\\Users\\alima"]
}
```

(And if it still doesn’t attach, try adding `"--transport","stdio"` here too—most servers default to stdio, but it won’t hurt.)

## 6) Optional: test with MCP Inspector

This isolates Claude Code from the equation:

```bash
# In one terminal (STDIO mode):
BRAVE_API_KEY="BSA..." npx -y @brave/brave-search-mcp-server --transport stdio

# In another:
npx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector npx -y @brave/brave-search-mcp-server --transport stdio
```

The Brave README shows inspector usage and confirms STDIO support. ([GitHub][1])

---

### TL;DR

* Add `--transport stdio` to the Brave server args.
* Ensure `BRAVE_API_KEY` is set in the env.
* Make sure `npx` is in PATH (or hard-path it).
* If it still times out, increase `MCP_TIMEOUT`.

If you paste your current `.mcp.json` (with the key redacted), I’ll patch it for you line-by-line.

**One more thing:** since your API key was pasted here in plain text, it’s safest to **rotate it** in the Brave dashboard and update the new value in your config. The Brave README links to the dashboard where you can regenerate keys. ([GitHub][1])

[1]: https://github.com/brave/brave-search-mcp-server "GitHub - brave/brave-search-mcp-server"
[2]: https://brave.com/search/api/guides/use-with-claude-desktop-with-mcp/?utm_source=chatgpt.com "How to add Brave Search to Claude Desktop with MCP"
[3]: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/79262030/could-not-start-mcp-server-for-brave-search-in-computer-use-and-claude-desktop?utm_source=chatgpt.com "Could not start MCP server for Brave Search in Computer ..."
[4]: https://docs.anthropic.com/en/docs/claude-code/mcp?utm_source=chatgpt.com "Connect Claude Code to tools via MCP"

heres info about vercel mcp: explain in detail why vercel mcp appears to not exist, im trying to install on caude code and running into issues
Short version: Vercel MCP **does** exist—but it’s not something you “install” as a local package inside Claude Code. It’s a **hosted, remote MCP server** that you connect to over HTTP and then OAuth into. If you were trying to `npx vercel-mcp` or searching npm for “vercel mcp,” you’ll hit dead ends or community-made packages—hence the “it doesn’t exist” feeling.

Here’s what trips people up and how to fix it:

# Why it looks like it “doesn’t exist”

1. **It’s a hosted server, not an npm package.**
   The official endpoint is `https://mcp.vercel.com`. You add it to Claude Code via `claude mcp add …` (HTTP transport), then authenticate with `/mcp`. You don’t install a local binary called “vercel-mcp.” ([Vercel][1], [Anthropic][2])

2. **There are similarly named community projects.**
   You’ll see repos/packages like `@open-mcp/vercel`, “vercel-api-mcp,” or “vercel-mcp” that are **not** the official Vercel server. They can work, but they’re third-party and configured differently (often as `npx …` stdio servers with your own API key). That naming overlap is the source of a lot of confusion. ([npm][3], [Glama – MCP Hosting Platform][4], [LobeHub][5])

3. **Approved clients + OAuth.**
   Vercel’s server requires OAuth and only supports specific AI clients they’ve approved. Claude Code is supported, but you must be on a recent version and complete the `/mcp` login flow; otherwise you’ll just see “Needs login.” ([Vercel][1])

4. **Windows quirk:** OAuth auth inside Claude Code works on macOS and **WSL**. If you’re on native Windows **without** WSL, the `/mcp` OAuth flow won’t work—use WSL, Claude Desktop, or another supported client to complete authentication. ([Anthropic][2])

5. **Adapter/package rename noise.**
   If you’re reading blogs/code about `@vercel/mcp-adapter`, note it was renamed/moved (`mcp-handler`). That’s for building your own MCP servers on Vercel—not needed just to use **Vercel’s** hosted server—another source of “where is it?” confusion. ([npm][6])

# The correct way to add Vercel MCP to Claude Code

```bash
# 1) Make sure you’re on a recent Claude Code
npm install -g @anthropic-ai/claude-code

# 2) From any project folder, add Vercel’s hosted MCP (general access)
claude mcp add --transport http vercel https://mcp.vercel.com

# (Optional) Project-specific context (auto-fills team/project)
claude mcp add --transport http vercel-myapp https://mcp.vercel.com/<teamSlug>/<projectSlug>

# 3) Launch Claude Code, then authenticate the server
claude
/mcp   # follow the browser login to Vercel and finish OAuth
```

This is the officially documented path for Claude Code, and it’s the reason you won’t find a “vercel-mcp” binary to install. ([Vercel][1], [Anthropic][2])

# Common errors → fixes

* **“Needs login” in Claude Code** → run `/mcp` and finish the OAuth flow in your browser. If you’re on Windows, use **WSL** or Claude Desktop to complete OAuth. ([Anthropic][2])
* **“Project slug and Team slug are required”** → connect using the project-scoped URL: `https://mcp.vercel.com/<teamSlug>/<projectSlug>`. This passes context automatically. ([Vercel][1])
* **Tried `npx vercel-mcp` and got “command not found”** → that’s a community pattern; it’s not the official server. Either use the official hosted server (above), or intentionally install a third-party Vercel MCP (be sure you trust it, provide `VERCEL_API_KEY`, and expect different tool coverage). ([npm][3])
* **Nothing happens after adding the server** → update Claude Code (`npm i -g @anthropic-ai/claude-code`), then `claude mcp list` to verify the server is registered, launch `claude`, and run `/mcp`. ([Anthropic][2])
* **Corporate SSO or blocked popups** → if your org enforces SSO, make sure the OAuth completes for the same Vercel account/team you want to manage; allow the popup and verify you’re authorizing the correct team.

# Quick sanity checks once connected

Ask Claude Code something trivial to verify tools are live, e.g.:

* “Search the Vercel docs for ‘Edge Config’ and summarize” (public docs tool)
* “List my recent deployments for `<project>` and show failing logs” (requires OAuth)
  These are exactly the capabilities the official server exposes. ([Vercel][1])

- New MCP "project" scope now allows you to add MCP servers to .mcp.json files and commit them to your repository

## 0.2.49

- Previous MCP server scopes have been renamed: previous "project" scope is now "local" and "global" scope is now "user"

## 0.2.47

- Press Tab to auto-complete file and folder names
- Press Shift + Tab to toggle auto-accept for file edits
- Automatic conversation compaction for infinite conversation length (toggle with /config)

## 0.2.44

- Ask Claude to make a plan with thinking mode: just say 'think' or 'think harder' or even 'ultrathink'

## 0.2.41

- MCP server startup timeout can now be configured via MCP_TIMEOUT environment variable
- MCP server startup no longer blocks the app from starting up

## 0.2.37

- New /release-notes command lets you view release notes at any time
- `claude config add/remove` commands now accept multiple values separated by commas or spaces

## 0.2.36

- Import MCP servers from Claude Desktop with `claude mcp add-from-claude-desktop`
- Add MCP servers as JSON strings with `claude mcp add-json <n> <json>`

## 0.2.34

- Vim bindings for text input - enable with /vim or /config

## 0.2.32

- Interactive MCP setup wizard: Run "claude mcp add" to add MCP servers with a step-by-step interface
- Fix for some PersistentShell issues

## 0.2.31

- Custom slash commands: Markdown files in .claude/commands/ directories now appear as custom slash commands to insert prompts into your conversation
- MCP debug mode: Run with --mcp-debug flag to get more information about MCP server errors

## 0.2.30

- Added ANSI color theme for better terminal compatibility
- Fixed issue where slash command arguments weren't being sent properly
- (Mac-only) API keys are now stored in macOS Keychain

## 0.2.26

- New /approved-tools command for managing tool permissions
- Word-level diff display for improved code readability
- Fuzzy matching for slash commands

## 0.2.21

- Fuzzy matching for /commands
